<TITLE> Turkish soldier killed in separatist attack </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 TUNCELI, Turkey, Nov 7 (bdnews24.com/Reuters) - A Turkish soldier was killed late on Tuesday when Kurdish guerrillas fired on a police station in Tunceli province, security sources said on Wednesday. The attack came a day after US President George W. Bush told Turkish Prime Minister Tayyip Erdogan that Washington was committed to countering the outlawed Kurdistan Workers Party (PKK), which both countries consider a terrorist organisation. The two countries said they planned to share intelligence on PKK activities to be able to hunt down and stop the rebels from attacking targets within Turkey from bases in northern Iraq. The statements helped ease concerns about an imminent major Turkish military operation against the PKK in northern Iraq, although Erdogan said after his meeting with Bush in Washington that action against the PKK was still planned. He did not specify the size of the operation. Turkey has assembled 100,000 troops at the border with Iraq, readying for a cross-border operation into northern Iraq where some 3,000 PKK guerrillas are based. Washington has urged NATO-ally Turkey not to carry out a major offensive, fearing it could destabilise northern Iraq and escalate into a bigger regional crisis. Nearly 40,000 people have been killed in the conflict that began in 1984 when PKK guerrillas took up arms to fight for a Kurdish homeland in southeastern Turkey. Security sources said one person was also injured in Tuesday's attack on a paramilitary police station near Tunceli. The deaths of more than 40 soldiers in recent weeks has sparked a huge public outcry in Turkey, with calls for an offensive against the the PKK based in northern Ira
